WEBVTT

00:00.930 --> 00:02.765
Ah, you know what?
Just remind me.

00:02.799 --> 00:05.067
I got to write a thank-you note
to the guy who invented waffles.

00:05.244 --> 00:09.482
The recipe first appeared
in <i>Le Ménagier de Paris,</i> a book

00:09.483 --> 00:12.018
a husband wrote for his wife
in the 14th century.

00:12.052 --> 00:14.487
Since he's dead,
a note would be pointless.

00:14.521 --> 00:17.490
I pity the men who aren't
married to you, Bones.

00:17.524 --> 00:19.359
Booth, did you see
what Christine brought home

00:19.393 --> 00:20.593
from preschool?

00:20.627 --> 00:22.061
Hey, look at
that, huh?

00:22.096 --> 00:24.464
15th place winner
in an egg race. Huh.

00:24.498 --> 00:26.632
Our little girl's
a champion.

00:26.667 --> 00:29.135
Booth, there are only
15 children in the class.

00:29.169 --> 00:30.603
What do you want me to do?

00:30.637 --> 00:32.372
Get her a trainer
so we could work her harder?

00:32.406 --> 00:34.440
If she's 15th,
that means that she lost.

00:34.475 --> 00:36.976
Children need to understand
what losing means.

00:37.011 --> 00:38.911
It's an egg race.

00:38.946 --> 00:41.280
When I was a child,
I played blackjack with Max,

00:41.315 --> 00:42.682
and he never let me win.

00:42.716 --> 00:44.117
I lost my allowance,

00:44.151 --> 00:46.019
but I got a realistic view
of the world.

00:46.053 --> 00:47.453
Your dad took your allowance?

00:47.488 --> 00:49.856
Won it. Actually,
he won the marker he gave me

00:49.890 --> 00:52.392
that said he owed me the allowance.
I don't think

00:52.426 --> 00:54.394
we should use your father as
an example here. It's not...

00:54.428 --> 00:56.062
Oh. Brennan.

00:56.096 --> 00:58.498
Okay, I'm on my way.
Wait. Wait. Wait a second.

00:58.532 --> 01:00.700
What about the waffle I just made you?
Sorry.

01:00.734 --> 01:02.168
A body's on its way to the lab.

01:02.202 --> 01:03.836
More for you.
I'll call if it concerns you.

01:03.871 --> 01:07.040
I got waffles flying
all over the place here.

01:08.142 --> 01:10.743
That's hot. That's hot.

01:13.847 --> 01:16.049
The remains are
in the pig troughs?

01:16.083 --> 01:19.652
Yes. I am setting up
a filtration system

01:19.686 --> 01:22.755
that will allow us to separate
liquid in the pig slop

01:22.790 --> 01:25.191
from any human remains,

01:25.225 --> 01:28.428
such as tissue,
bones, organs...

01:28.462 --> 01:30.963
But you're not waiting.
I was told

01:30.998 --> 01:33.833
the body was dumped
on a pig farm in Virginia.

01:33.867 --> 01:35.368
Yeah.

01:35.402 --> 01:37.870
So the noise of the pigs feeding
woke up the farmer,

01:37.905 --> 01:39.639
so he was able to stop them

01:39.673 --> 01:41.641
before they finished eating
all the human remains.

01:41.675 --> 01:43.443
I need an intern.
Where's Oliver Wells?

01:43.477 --> 01:45.278
Out of town on family business.

01:45.312 --> 01:48.114
Dr. Brennan, Dr. Hodgins,
you remember Dr. Filmore?

01:48.148 --> 01:49.749
It's our favorite Canadian

01:49.783 --> 01:51.484
forensic podiatrist.

01:51.518 --> 01:53.119
Hello, Dr. Hodgins.

01:53.153 --> 01:54.787
Dr. Brennan, it's a pleasure
to be working with you again.

01:54.822 --> 01:57.457
I'm afraid there will be
no pleasure, Dr. Filmore.

01:57.491 --> 01:59.325
His field is forensic podiatry.

01:59.359 --> 02:02.061
Dr. Filmore is writing a report

02:02.096 --> 02:03.796
at the request
of the FBI

02:03.831 --> 02:05.431
and the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police

02:05.466 --> 02:08.101
on cooperation between
the United States and Canada

02:08.134 --> 02:09.936
in the field of
forensic sciences.

02:09.970 --> 02:12.038
It's the first trans-border
study in forensic cooperation

02:12.072 --> 02:13.739
between our two
great nations.

02:13.774 --> 02:15.141
No. I can't allow that.

02:15.175 --> 02:17.210
We're in the middle
of an investigation.

02:17.244 --> 02:19.278
Hmm.

02:19.313 --> 02:21.447
What are you doing?

02:21.482 --> 02:22.949
Notes for my report.

02:22.983 --> 02:25.318
"Check American definition
of 'cooperation.'"

02:25.352 --> 02:26.953
Dr. Filmore

02:26.987 --> 02:28.588
will be your intern so he can

02:28.622 --> 02:29.956
observe firsthand that

02:29.990 --> 02:32.425
our definition
of cooperation is the same

02:32.459 --> 02:33.759
as our neighbors to the north.

02:33.794 --> 02:35.261
By his own admission,

02:35.295 --> 02:37.263
he's familiar with only 25%

02:37.297 --> 02:39.398
of the bones in the human body.

02:39.433 --> 02:42.135
Actually, I just completed
my PhD in forensic anthropology,

02:42.169 --> 02:45.505
so I am now fully qualified
to work with you...

02:45.539 --> 02:47.340
as a peer.

02:48.976 --> 02:51.110
Then that settles it.

02:51.145 --> 02:53.045
Now, if you'll
excuse me.

02:53.080 --> 02:54.647
Put on some gloves.

02:54.681 --> 02:57.083
We're looking for human remains
in these troughs.

02:57.117 --> 02:58.851
We might not be able to recover

02:58.886 --> 03:00.286
a complete
skeleton because...

03:00.320 --> 03:02.221
Because pigs eat human bones.

03:02.256 --> 03:04.323
I grew up
on a farm in Manitoba.

03:11.665 --> 03:13.366
Angela...

03:13.400 --> 03:16.469
Oh, hey. I can't do anything
until I have a skull,

03:16.503 --> 03:18.738
so I thought I'd just
create something alive.

03:18.772 --> 03:20.339
Not why I'm here.

03:20.374 --> 03:22.742
It's, uh...

03:22.776 --> 03:24.544
<i>Science Monthly</i>
just contacted me

03:24.578 --> 03:27.180
about their Outstanding Women
of Science issue.

03:27.214 --> 03:28.981
Oh. Brennan again?

03:29.016 --> 03:31.851
No. Me.

03:32.886 --> 03:34.487
They want me this year.

03:34.521 --> 03:37.857
Oh, my God!
Cam, that's fantastic!

03:37.891 --> 03:39.759
Congratulations!

03:39.793 --> 03:42.228
I should be happy,
but I just feel uncomfortable.

03:43.664 --> 03:44.931
Brennan?

03:44.965 --> 03:48.501
Yeah. She can sometimes feel...

03:48.535 --> 03:50.503
I don't know how to say it.

03:50.537 --> 03:52.672
That all awards
should go to her?

03:52.706 --> 03:54.907
And I don't really care.

03:54.942 --> 03:56.542
I could just
tell the magazine no.

03:56.577 --> 03:58.444
Oh, no. Don't be ridiculous.

03:58.478 --> 04:00.846
This is...
this is a huge honor,

04:00.881 --> 04:02.915
and we're all going
to celebrate this,

04:02.950 --> 04:04.550
including Brennan.

04:04.585 --> 04:06.452
You have to
enjoy this.

04:06.486 --> 04:09.755
Smile. You deserve it.

04:15.028 --> 04:16.629
Aah. This will be easier.

04:16.663 --> 04:18.130
So, the pump
creates suction

04:18.165 --> 04:20.466
and delivers the contents
of the troughs into this

04:20.500 --> 04:22.535
sluice box,
which will separate liquid

04:22.569 --> 04:25.037
from particulates greater than
.03 millimeters.

04:25.072 --> 04:26.706
Quite the impressive
contrivance, Dr. Hodgins.

04:26.740 --> 04:28.407
Right? All right.

04:28.442 --> 04:29.575
Here we go.

04:32.012 --> 04:34.580
- Yeah!
- Oh!

04:34.615 --> 04:36.215
It appears to working.

04:36.250 --> 04:37.283
You know, this death

04:37.317 --> 04:38.751
might just be an accident.

04:38.785 --> 04:40.219
We had a farmhand

04:40.254 --> 04:41.520
who fell into the trough after

04:41.555 --> 04:43.256
drinking to excess.
The pigs must have

04:43.290 --> 04:45.491
thought he was delicious,
because there was nothing left.

04:45.525 --> 04:47.093
Well, considering
this person was

04:47.127 --> 04:49.662
dismembered, I would
rule out an accident.

04:49.696 --> 04:51.397
Yes.

04:53.867 --> 04:56.335
Oh. Ah.

04:56.370 --> 04:58.704
Dark brown hair.
Definitely human.

04:58.739 --> 05:00.439
Well, the greater

05:00.474 --> 05:02.575
sciatic notch indicates a male.

05:02.609 --> 05:05.011
The auricular surface indicates
an age range

05:05.045 --> 05:07.013
between 29 and 35.

05:07.047 --> 05:08.914
Huh. A central incisor.

05:08.949 --> 05:11.751
Not in any way connected
with the foot, of course.

05:11.785 --> 05:15.321
This spatula shape indicates
the victim was Caucasian.

05:15.355 --> 05:17.990
Told you it would work, huh?

05:20.894 --> 05:22.728
Well,

05:22.763 --> 05:24.330
it's not the filter.

05:24.364 --> 05:25.398
Can you hold that?
Yes.

05:25.432 --> 05:26.499
It's got to be

05:26.533 --> 05:28.768
the hose.

05:28.802 --> 05:30.403
Hey. Good news.

05:30.437 --> 05:32.638
Cam got a call from
<i>Science Monthly.</i>

05:32.673 --> 05:34.006
They announced this year's

05:34.041 --> 05:35.875
Outstanding Women
of Science award.

05:35.909 --> 05:37.243
Why did they call Cam?

05:37.277 --> 05:38.757
Why didn't they just
call me directly?

05:40.113 --> 05:42.948
Because Cam is getting
the award, sweetie.

05:42.983 --> 05:44.784
Wow!

05:44.818 --> 05:47.153
That's great.
Yes, I'm very happy for her.

05:47.187 --> 05:49.689
And you're happy
for her, too, Brennan.

05:49.723 --> 05:51.357
Very happy.

05:51.391 --> 05:52.992
Because she's your friend.

05:53.026 --> 05:54.760
Yes.

05:54.795 --> 05:57.830
Just the-the descriptor
is "outstanding."

05:57.864 --> 06:00.599
All right, we're all good to go.

06:00.634 --> 06:01.867
You know, <i>Science Monthly</i> is

06:01.902 --> 06:04.370
an exceptional mag...
Oh! My.

06:06.673 --> 06:07.907
Don't move,

06:07.941 --> 06:08.908
Dr. Filmore.

06:08.942 --> 06:10.343
You're covered in evidence.

06:10.377 --> 06:11.944
It's no problem.

06:11.978 --> 06:14.146
Just like being
back on the farm.

06:15.349 --> 06:16.849
Oh, here's a piece...

06:16.883 --> 06:19.151
Thank you.
...that's important.

